ex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on a collaboration between historians of Chinese and European politics, this volume offers a first comprehensive overview of current research on political communication in middle-period European and Chinese history. The chapters present new work on the sources and processes of political communication in European and Chinese history partly through juxtaposing and combining formerly separate historiographies and partly through direct comparison. Contrary to earlier comparative work on empires and state formation, which aimed to explain similarities and differences with encompassing models and new theories of divergence, the goal is to further conversations between historians by engaging regional historiographies from the bottom up.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunication in politicsxHistoryzChina. 0aCommunication in politicsxHistoryzEurope. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aPolitical communication, medieval and early modern history, Chinese history, European history, comparative history, global history.1 aBlockmans, Wim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossler, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Weerdt, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbrey, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenet, Jean-Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGowers, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 